<section id="interpretation">
    <h2>Reading Your Results Like a Cardiologist</h2>

    <h3>Red Flags That Demand Action</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Any coronary calcium:</strong> You have disease, period</li>
        <li><strong>Fasting insulin &gt; 10:</strong> Metabolic disaster brewing</li>
        <li><strong>Small dense LDL &gt; 30%:</strong> Arterial damage ongoing</li>
        <li><strong>hs-CRP &gt; 1.0:</strong> Find the inflammation source</li>
        <li><strong>Multiple "borderline" results:</strong> Pattern = problem</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What Your Doctor Won't Tell You</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>"Normal" ranges are based on sick populations</li>
        <li>"Normal" glucose with high insulin = pre-disease</li>
        <li>Optimal is dramatically different from "normal"</li>
        <li>Trends matter more than single values</li>
        <li>Root cause investigation is essential</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="critical-box">
        <strong>The Bottom Line:</strong>
        If your doctor says your "cholesterol is fine" based on a basic panel, find a new doctor. Real cardiovascular prevention requires real testing.
    </div>
</section>
